subtitles_text: >> JEFF: Previously on Survivor:
Kucha and Ogakor merged into one tribe at equal numbers with five
members each, calling themselves Barramundi.
The tribe set up camp on a new beach and started from scratch.
( cheering ) In a test of endurance, the
first individual immunity challenge lasted over ten hours.
Tina stepped down to give the more vulnerable Keith immunity,
so that the ex-Ogakor tribe could take the advantage at
Tribal Council. So, we're ruling this a deadlock
vote. Colby and Jeff were deadlocked
into tie, so Jeff's votes at previously Tribal Councils
tipped the scales, and Jeff was voted out of the tribe.
Nine survivors remain. Who will be voted out tonight?
>> RODGER: It's a late-sleeping bunch, isn't it?
>> ALICIA: Yeah. >> RODGER: A lot different

>> RODGER: And, you know, every time from now on, when we're...
when we're around the fire, we will think of it.
>> ALICIA: Yep. >> RODGER: After the last Tribal
Council, I just felt like we had been outwitted by Ogakor.
Kucha's tribe could be picked off very easily.
They're in a good position to do that.
We could be an extinct tribe, no longer on the face of the earth.
To me, it's, uh, one-on-one and every man for himself from here

I am in it to win just like anybody else.
I'm going to give it my best shot.
My game plan right now to try to assure my survival is try to
keep catching fish. Ooh, yes.

probably not be the person that is supplying 'em with the food.
